    "body": "Some more insights:\n\n@pinebit looked into it as well. He found out that replacing `StatusBaseText` with `Text` removes the flicker. Also when setting `renderType: Text.NativeRendering` (which essentially renders a default font), the flicker is gone.\n\nSo this were indications that it's related to the font we're using specifically (`Inter`). I've tried different formats of the font (`.ttf` instead of `.otf`) and the flicker still exists.\n\nI've even replaced the font with a completely different one (`Ubuntu`) and the the flicker also happens. \n\nBut again, only when using `font.weight: Font.Medium`.\n\nI still think there's a possibility that scaling the font doesn't work well:\n\n> There's a chance that maybe there's a QML bug when scaling the font.weight, but I can't say for sure.\n\nAs a matter of fact, even though we're loading all different shapes of a font, we only use `baseFont` in StatusQ and then use `font.weight` to set the weight of the font. I don't think `QML` automatically knows that we're now interested in using the `-Bold` or `-Medium` variant of the font.",
